&lt;p&gt;The plant was being used to manufacture, store and dispatch finished and semi-finished pyrotechnics devices classed as ‘category IV’ and ‘category V’ under Italian public safety legislation (Consolidated Public Safety Laws or ‘TULPS’ as per its Italian acronym), as well as smaller fireworks of the type permitted for general sale to the public. The plant has a surface area of approximately 45&amp;nbsp;350&amp;nbsp;m² and a wire mesh fence. It is located in a hilly area, on a slope that is not particularly steep. The nearest two populated areas are located approximately 1&amp;nbsp;km and 490&amp;nbsp;m away from the plant. There is railway and road infrastructure nearby (a state highway is approximately 1.8&amp;nbsp;km away and a railway line approximately 2.1&amp;nbsp;km), and the nearest railway station is approximately 2.5&amp;nbsp;km from the plant as the crow flies. There are no industrial premises, public offices, schools or hospitals within 1.0&amp;nbsp;km of the plant. There are production facilities around 2.2&amp;nbsp;km away, beyond the affected area for emergency planning purposes. None of the activities regulated by Council Directive 96/82/EC are present. An underground methane pipeline with a diameter of DN&amp;nbsp;150 runs along the local road that provides access to the plant (located to the east of the plant), and there is a 20&amp;nbsp;kV overhead power line at the plant’s eastern boundary.&amp;nbsp;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The operations carried out at the plant were as follows:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Raw materials and/or semi-finished products were delivered and stored in suitable premises;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Fireworks were manufactured by assembling pre-packaged components, namely coloured and/or explosive pyrotechnic mixtures, always hand-mixed and sealed in cardboard or polyethylene containers;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Finished products were dispatched.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The production and storage area used for the activities described consisted of nine buildings with different uses assigned to each, known as buildings A, B, C, D, E, F, G, H and I (figure 2), as well as a thermal power facility. The safety distances laid down in national legislation had been respected in the plant’s design. Up to 21.5 tonnes of explosives in total could be kept in buildings A, B and G. A description of the plant and the maximum authorised product quantities is as follows:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Building A — storage of up to 1.5 tonnes of black powder of differing grain sizes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Building B (B1 and B2) — storage of up to 10 tonnes of explosive finished products (categories IV and V).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Building C (C1 and C2) — prepared explosive workshop and hydraulic press used to press small quantities of dampened black powder (a maximum of 500&amp;nbsp;g per cycle) into cardboard cartridges using special moulds. Reinforced concrete and bulletproof glass separated the press from the worker operating it.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Building D — workshop and coloured blend warehouse. The — entirely manual — production work carried out in area D1 (where raw materials were blended together to produce the explosive mixture) concerned small amounts of material, producing mixture weighing between 2 and 10&amp;nbsp;kg. The materials originated in building F and the prepared mixtures were transported to building H. Area D2 contained a cement mixer, which was used to make up colour batches.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Building E — offices, canteen and service premises, located outside the fenced-off area in which explosives were manufactured and stored.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Building F (F1 and F2) — non-explosive raw material warehouse, with products separated into oxidising, flammable and combustible.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Building G (G1 and G2) — category-IV and -V explosive finished products warehouse, storing up to 10 tonnes of material. Both fireworks produced on-site and fireworks purchased from other factories for sale were stored here.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Building H — workshop used for preparing, finishing, filling and packaging fireworks.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Building I — canopy-covered milling facility. Inert materials were present in this area, which was used to blend coloured mixtures and dry the blends, as well as to house machinery.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;TPF — thermal power facility.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;According to the fire brigade, the firm also stored at the plant explosive material entrusted to it by the police for safekeeping after being seized; such material was being stored in the finished product warehouses (buildings B and G) at the time of the accident. The accident affected all the materials present on the plant premises.&amp;nbsp; The way the seized material was being stored does not seem to be linked to any of the explanations put forward for why the accident happened.&lt;/p&gt;
